events.name: Women Techmakers Frankfurt - Opening Talk
events.description:
</a>

As a part of the Women Techmakers powered by the Google Developer Group we are opening our chapter in the Rhein Main Region.

Our goal is to connect, share experiences, learn and improve together.

Join us at the opening event with wine, snacks and interesting talks from inspiring women in tech to celebrate the start of the program in Frankfurt.

Agenda:

18:30 Drinks & Snacks: Doors open

19:00 Welcome/Our story (Anja Schumann and Olga Kostova, Women Techmakers)

Anja established WTM in <a href="https://www.meetup.com/de-DE/womentechmakershamburg/">Hamburg. She is currently working as a Business IT Consultant in Frankfurt and happy to be back in the Rhein Main Region that reminds her of her life as a student in Marburg. She has a passion for entrepreneurship and also launched her own app business to the app store this year. Before that she was transforming business processes in E-Commerce and Supply Chain Management for companies like Tchibo and Lenovo.

Olga is a Digital Data Analyst. She is currently consulting a German Company in Hamburg but constantly traveling the world. Anja and Olga met at one of the Meetups in Hamburg.

19:20 Welcome from Rest of the Google Developer Group Frankfurt (GDG Frankfurt)

19:30 Interview with a Woman in Tech: Christa Koenen, CEO DB Systel

20:00 *Break*

20:15 Women in Tech/ Nicole Göbel, Director Travel & Transportation Accenture & Theresa Bihn Java Software Engineer and Tech Lead

Theresa is an Agilist, a Solution Designer and a Software Engineer (Java). She works since nearly 6 years for Accenture as an IT-Consultant and helps her clients to build innovative, sustainable software. Theresa wrote her first program when she was 15 years old and is ever since convinced that only a diverse group of software engineers can build innovative software that truly solve the customer’s problems.
Theresa was keynote speaker at the WJAX 2015, wrote an article for informatik-aktuell, gave several interviews, won the Panda Women Leadership Contest in 2014, and supports students in their last school year to gain their first IT-Project experience by building mobile apps since 5 years.

Theresa’s vision is to become a role-model for women and girls who want to start their career in tech.

Nicole Göbel is a managing director at Accenture, a global consultancy and professional services company with over[masked] employees in more than 120 countries. Here she focuses on the travel and transportation industry. Nicole holds a degree in tourism economics with majors in computer sciences and marketing and has more than 20 years of experience in project work within the industry e.g. at airlines, tour operators and railways, always at the cross-roads of functional departments and IT.

20:45 Networking and Drinks

22:00 Closing

Women Techmakers is Google’s brand and global program for women in technology. Women Techmakers provides visibility, community, and resources for women in technology to drive innovation and participation in the field. Women Techmakers events are designed to promote an environment of inclusivity for women in technology, as well as celebrate women leading the industry. We want to advance, grow and celebrate women developers, designers, and technology entrepreneurs.

events.name: Digital Transformation
events.description:
Every business is a digital business

Digital transformation is the reinvention of an organization through the use of digital technology to improve the way it performs and serves its constituents. Digital refers to the use of technology that generates, stores and processes data.

The term transformation refers to a fundamental change to an organization's day-to-day business from the types of products and services it produces to how it delivers them. Simply implementing technology alone doesn't bring about digital transformation but changing an organization to reap the potential of those technologies does. 

In spite of all the benefits, digital transformation is a struggle for many organizations and there is no one blueprint for success

This meetup is about... understanding the hype behind 'Digital Transformation'. Our speakers will give us some insights what happens on the road to digital transformation.

Agenda: 

• 18:30 Doors open (Room Jupiter): Snacks & Drinks

• 19:00 Welcome (WTM Frankfurt)

• 19:05 Digital Transformation @Cofinpro (Cofinpro)

• 19:25 Digital transformation vs "Innovation Theater" -
what we learned at KfW (Jure Zakotnik & Ingmar Müller, Digital Office KfW)

• 19:45 Break - time to refill your drinks

• 20:00 Digital Transformation @DB Systel (Claudia Stützel, CIO DB Systel)

• 20:25 The challenge of Change (Michael Beckmann) 

• 20:45 Snacks & Discuss

events.name: Choosing your first Frontend Javascript framework
events.description:
Everyone has differing opinions on which Frontend framework is “best”, which one is easiest to pick up, and which one is most sought after in the industry. Is it React? Ember? Polymer? Vue? Well, we won’t answer that question for you, but we do promise to shed some light on a few of the most popular frameworks today, dive into the code, and help inspire you to try something new and find your own preference.

This workshop is best-suited for those with some basic knowledge of Javascript. We also ask that you bring along your own laptop (with an editor installed and node) to the event so you can write some code along with us. We have limited space for this event, and would like to give preference to women - so ladies make sure you sign up soon!

Please use this link to secure your spot at the event, and tell us which framework interests you most: https://goo.gl/forms/yKLmjitPyEuwJMHE2

The event will start at 6:30pm, with snacks and drinks provided courtesy of Record Evolution. Looking forward to seeing you there!

Agenda:

6:30pm - Doors open (Help yourself to snacks and drinks!)

6:45pm - Intro from WTM

7:00pm - Interactive Demos (React, Vue.js and Polymer)

8:30pm - Open Discussion / Comparisons / Q&A

events.name: Learn to Read Microexpressions
events.description:
Learning how to decode the face is like having a super power.

The face is the window into the soul–if you know how to read it. The good news is we can already tell a lot about someone by their face. That sounds like the popular series 'Lie to me'? Knowing how to read and interpret microexpressions is an essential part of understanding nonverbal behavior and reading people. Susanne Primbs is our special guest and will tell you everything you need to know about microexpressions

Agenda:

18:30 Doors open - Networking

19:00 Welcome!

19:15 Microexpressionen - Susanne Primbs
(Program Manager HR Enterprise Standards for Europe & Russia CIS)

20:00 Open Discussion about Microexpressions

Google IWD'18

Google strives to cultivate a wholly inclusive workplace around the globe. A key component of that vision is empowering women to pursue their dreams and build tools that change the world.

Having a diversity of perspectives and ideas leads to better decision-making, more relevant products, and makes the industry much more interesting. We believe that by creating the right environments, programs and policies, women in tech are better positioned to drive transformational change in the industry and beyond.

events.name: DACHFest 2018
events.description: THE HUMAN SIDE OF TECH DACHFest is a two-day conference focused on making a difference. Discover all the different ways in which emerging technology is transforming lives, find out how to make your apps and websites friendly towards everyone, learn the secrets of building and nurturing a diverse community — let our speakers surprise and inspire you! And don't forget to make new friends: there will be plenty of opportunities to meet people passionate about your favorite things. Join us and get your ticket here (deals, discounts and scholarships available): https://dachfest.com/ For the community, by the community DACHFest is a part of the global DevFest series of events, and it is organized by tech communities — Google Developer Groups and Women Techmakers chapters — from not just one, but three different countries: Germany, Austria, and Switzerland. Joining forces has enabled us to build a conference the way we have always wanted to: non-profit and volunteer-run, friendly towards everyone, committed to diversity and inclusion, and making a real impact.

events.name: Frontend Debugging BYOB (Bring Your Own Bugs!) 🐛
events.description:
We've all been there, stuck for days on one pesky little 🐞in the code, scouring Google and Stack Overflow until all the links have turned purple 🙈. There's got to be a better way, you say! Well, we are going to show you 😉

Join us on May 15th at 6:30pm for an interactive debugging session, where we show you the tools and tips you need to become a debugging Pro! From the strategies needed to tackle the problem, to the tools you need to solve it quickly, we'll cover it all with live examples. The best part of all - you are invited to "bring your OWN bugs" to the party, and together we'll help you debug them.

If you have a bug you'd like help squashing, please email [masked] prior to the event with the following info:
1. Github or CodePen link to your bug
2. Description of bug (Expected behaviour vs Actual behaviour & how to reproduce it)
3. Environment which you found the bug in (IE11, Chrome, iOS, Android, etc)

Though this event is mainly geared towards debugging for Frontend developers, the strategies can be applicable to all devs. All experience levels welcome!

6:30 - Doors Open & Networking
7:00 - Welcome from Women Techmakers Frankfurt
7:10 - Get to know Publicis Sapient - Holger Hellinger
7:25 - 8:30 - Strategies for Faster Debugging & Increased Productivity:
✅Mobile, cross-browser and unit test debugging - Daniela Valero
8:30 - BYOB debugging session
9:00 - Networking

Food and drinks will be provided 😊Thank you Publicis Sapient for hosting 🎉

Thanks a lot to our sponsor, DB Systel, for providing us with an awesome location at the top floor of the Silvertower! 👏

6:30 - Doors Open & Networking (Snacks + Drinks)
7:00 - Welcome from WTM Frankfurt & GDG Rhein-Main
7:10 - Overview how Cloud is fast forwarding our tech opportunities (Emily J. Ryan, Google Cloud Enablement)
7:30 - Docker & Kubernetes (Ronan, GDG)
8:00 - Our Special guest Emma Haruka Iwao*
8:40 - Networking

*) Emma Haruka Iwao is a Japanese computer scientist and cloud developer advocate at Google. In 2019 Haruka Iwao calculated the world's most accurate value of pi (π); which included 31.4 trillion digits, far past the previous record of 22 trillion.
Iwao joined Google as a Cloud Developer Advocate in 2015. She originally worked for Google in Tokyo, before moving to Seattle in 2019. Iwao offers training in the use of the Google Cloud Platform (GCP), as well as supporting application developers. She works to make cloud computing accessible for everyone, creating online demos and teaching materials.

events.name: Go Do Good Data (Co-Meetup with Frankfurt Data Science)
events.description:
GoDoGoodData
On 27 of June we are bringing Frankfurt Data Science, Women Techmakers and Women in AI communities together to talk about the most IMPACTFUL topic for humankind and nature - Multiplying social good by using Data and AI.

How many lives were saved with a help of predictive analytics in medical diagnostics? Hurricane Sandy, how many children were found under the ruins of houses and saved with a help of graph analytics? Hundreds and thousands. Oil spills diffusions are prevented with a help of deep learning of images made by satellites. Isn’t it all awesome?

We have great people on the stage and in the room, professional, inspiring and confident. Besides, we are inviting our audience to take part at our super-special fishbowl discussion.

18:00 - Doors open
19:00 - Welcome! Intro by WTM, Frankfurt Data Science and Women in AI
19:15 - Talks

TALK 1
SOCIAL CAUSE MATCHER
By Vidya Munde-Müller, Co-Founder of GiveTastic
Vidya founded a social startup that is matching our ❤ ❤ ❤ with a right charity organizations, so we can make a right contribution to the right organisation on the matter our hearts care most, all that - easy, seamless and with a help of AI.
www.givetastic.org
de.linkedin.com/in/vidyamundemueller

TALK 2
HOW SOCIAL ENTREPRENEURS ARE USING DATA TO DO GOOD
As heroes of the modern age, Social Entrepreneurs set out to change society for the better. Find out how data is playing a relevant role in their endeavours in this talk by Social Impact Lab Frankfurt incubation manager and Social Entrepreneurship Network Germany co-founder, Michael Wunsch.
http://schnuw.com
https://twitter.com/DrSchnuw
https://frankfurt.socialimpactlab.eu
http://www.send-ev.de

TALK 3
PASSION IS NOT ENOUGH
Andre Lange, Leader of local Rhein-Main Chapter of CorrelAid
650 voluntary data scientists, who have their normal daily full-time jobs, evenings are coding together deep learning algorithms to help mission-driven organisations to create more social good. How these people are doing that, is in this talk by Andre.
correlaid.org/en
de.linkedin.com/in/andre-lange-5a[masked]

20:30 - Fishbowl discussion
21:00 - Networking

LIVESTREAM｜www.youtube.com/c/FrankfurtDataScience

With Love,
FFM Data Science, Women Techmakers and Women in AI Teams

events.name: Let's talk about Cloud Security
events.description:
Let's talk about Cloud Security.

For businesses making the transition to the cloud, robust cloud security is imperative. Security threats are constantly evolving and becoming more sophisticated, and cloud computing is no less at risk than an on-premise environment. So let's take the chance to look into Cloud Security.

Agenda:
6:30 pm - Doors Open & Networking (Snacks + Drinks)
7:00 pm - Welcome from WTM Frankfurt & Google
7:15 pm - "Cloud security enablement for financial services digital transformation", Dr. Keyun Ruan, Computer Scientist & Author, Google
8:00 pm - "Gearing up for Future Financial Markets - Security & Compliance Approach for Public Cloud", Melinda Rentsch, Cloud Architect, Deutsche Börse
8:30 pm - "10 most common cloud security threats and how to handle them", Christine Deger, IT & Cybersecurity Expert, changeboxx
9:00 pm - Networking

About our speakers:

Keyun Ruan is a computer scientist and author with two published textbooks. She has been recognised internationally for her pioneering work on cloud forensics over the past decade. She is currently working on her second project around digital asset valuation and cyber risk measurement. She is the security & compliance specialist lead for financial services in EMEA at Google Cloud. More information can be found at www.ruankeyun.com

Melinda Rentsch is working in Cloud Team at Deutsche Börse. She joined DBAG in 2016 in IT Infrastructure & Operations as IT Junior Consultant. Since 2019 she is part of the Cloud team. She has a Master in Strategic Information Management.

Christine Deger is a cyber security expert with 18+ years of IT consulting experience, specialising in the fields of Finance, software development and healthcare. Christine is the author of the book "Cybersecurity – aus der Praxis für die Praxis."

events.name: Hacktoberfest Frankfurt 2019
events.description:
Welcome back to Hacktoberfest Frankfurt 2019!

Let's get together again to celebrate open source over food, drinks, and great company! Hacktoberfest is all about encouraging meaningful contributions to the open source ecosystem, and we would love to see you for the 2019 edition!

Come along to learn more about Open Source projects, commit code and network with fellow Open Source enthusiasts!

Register here: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/hacktoberfest-frankfurt-2019-tickets-71269742719?aff=womentechmakersfrankfurt

Location

DB Systel GmbH
Jürgen-Ponto-Platz 1
60329 Frankfurt am Main

Agenda*
17:00 - Doors Open
18:00 - Welcome & Introductions: Hacktoberfest Frankfurt 2019
18:15 - Open Source Talk (more info soon)
19:00 - Break with Drinks
19:15 - Open Source Talk (more info soon)
19:30 - Free Coding or Workshops & Lightning Talks (more info soon)
23:50 - End of Event

*The agenda is subject to change

All attendees are required to read and comply with our Code of Conduct: https://www.vuejsfrankfurt.de/about/coc.html

What is Hacktoberfest?
Hacktoberfest — brought to you by DigitalOcean in partnership DEV — is a month-long celebration of open source software. Maintainers are invited to guide would-be contributors towards issues that will help move the project forward, and contributors get the opportunity to give back to both projects they like, and ones they've just discovered. No contribution is too small—bug fixes and documentation updates are valid ways of participating.

Rules and Prizes
Hacktoberfest encourages more participation in the open source community, which grows bigger every year. Complete the 2019 challenge and earn a limited edition T-shirt.

First, sign up on the Hacktoberfest site. If you open up five pull requests between October 1 and October 31, you'll win a free, limited edition Hacktoberfest T-shirt. Pull requests do not have to be merged and accepted; as long as they've been opened between the very start of October 1 and the very end of October 31, they count towards a free T-shirt.

Find out more: https://hacktoberfest.digitalocean.com

Call for Speakers
Are you an Open Source maintainer, contributor, project owner or enthusiast who wants to share your project or journey into Open Source with the community in Frankfurt? No matter your speaking or open source experience, we want to hear from you! Please fill out this form to express your interest: https://forms.gle/6fmHXoPC9y332S1WA

If you have any questions, please contact us or the main organizers
Twitter: @hacktoberffm or https://twitter.com/hacktoberffm
Email: [masked]

events.name: Karriere-Skills und Sichtbarkeit! FidAR meets WTM at KfW
events.description:
*** Note: This event will be held in German. We apologize to our non-German speaking members. We will return to hosting English events as usual following this event :) ***

Karriere-Skills und Sichtbarkeit auf dem Weg zum Chefposten

Women Techmakers Frankfurt/ Rhein-Main und FidAR (Frauen in die Aufsichtsräte e.V.) gehen zusammen den folgenden Fragen nach: Was braucht es eigentlich, um heute erfolgreich Karriere zu machen? Welche formellen Voraussetzungen gibt es für die Arbeit in einem Aufsichtsrat? Wie sieht der Arbeitsalltag einer Aufsichtsrätin aus? Welche (digitalen) Skills sind gefordert und wie kann man diese entwickeln bzw. trainieren? Und gibt es eigentlich eine Jobbörse für Aufsichtsratsposten?

Wir freuen uns auf den Austausch mit Euch; Job-Board, interaktive Sessions sowie Networking Drinks & Snacks inklusive! Danke an dieser Stelle an unseren großzügigen Location-Partner KfW!

Da die Teilnehmerzahl begrenzt ist, bitten wir Euch um frühzeitige Anmeldung bzw. rechtzeitige Abmeldung, für den Fall, dass ihr Euer Ticket doch nicht nutzen können solltet.

AGENDA
18:30 Ankunft & Drinks & Networking
19:00 Herzlich Willkommen - KfW, Women Techmakers & FidAR.
19:15 WTM: Karrierethemen, die unsere Community bewegen. Theresa Bihn, Women Techmakers.
19:25 FidAR: Karrierethemen, die unsere Community bewegen. Bettina Laurick, Regionalvorstand FidAR
19:35 Drinks & Networking
19:50 BREAK OUT SESSION 1, "Anforderungen der Aufsichtsratarbeit" Christine Gärtner, Komitee FidAR Rhein-Main
19:50 BREAK OUT SESSION 2, "Sichtbarkeit"
Marina Zayats, Consultant Corporate Communication & Digital Personal Branding
20:40 Drinks & Networking
20:55 Erfahrungsaustausch im Plenum
Drinks & Networking

Bitte beachtet, das während der Veranstaltung Foto- und Videoaufnahmen entstehen, die unter anderem in den sozialen Medien veröffentlicht werden.

events.name: UX - How to design the future
events.description:
User experience (UX) design is a concept that has many dimensions, and it includes a bunch of different disciplines—such as interaction design, information architecture, visual design, usability, and human-computer interaction. But all these disciplines have one goal: “improve customer satisfaction and loyalty through the utility, ease of use, and pleasure provided in the interaction with a product".

We'll take a closer look at UX and its dimension during this Meetup together with Zuehlke in Eschborn. You can get there by train (S-Bahn) or by car (limited parking space is available).

Agenda
6.30 pm Doors Open at Zuehlke in Eschborn
7.00 pm Welcome WTM & Welcome Zuehlke
7.10 pm Changing role of UX Design and its role in projects today (Katharina Schlungs, Zuehlke)
7.40 pm UX journey of KSEDi (UX in practice) (Eva-Maria)
8.10 pm Tools of a digital gunslinger for innovation (Antanas Cikanauskas, Cocomore AG)
8.40 pm Networking

upcoming.name: International Women's Day Special 2020
upcoming.description:
We're celebrating Internation Women's Day 2020. Stay tuned for further information. Agenda will follow soon.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Google IWD'2020

Google strives to cultivate a wholly inclusive workplace around the globe. A key component of that vision is empowering women to pursue their dreams and build tools that change the world.

Having a diversity of perspectives and ideas leads to better decision-making, more relevant products, and makes the industry much more interesting. We believe that by creating the right environments, programs and policies, women in tech are better positioned to drive transformational change in the industry and beyond.
